#1 History of resected stage III colon adenocarcinoma
Mrs. Lincoln is recovering reasonably well from her hemicolectomy for colon adenocarcinoma.  Her tumor was a T2, N1, M0 (stage III cancer), and was grade 4 by histology.  We discussed at length prognosis and the risk and benefits of chemotherapy.  We discussed that if chemotherapy were to be considered, it would likely be with single-agent capecitabine for six-months and that this might reduce her risk of recurrence by approximately 7%.  Mrs. Lincoln is not interested in receiving chemotherapy at this time and would prefer rather to be followed by Dr. Hall.  I think that this is completely reasonable.  I would recommend clinical exam every three-months or so with blood work including CEA.  CT scans of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis could be performed initially every three to six-months for the first couple of years after which point they could be lengthened to once yearly.  Mrs. Lincoln understands and expresses agreement with the plan.  I have given her my card in case she has further questions or concerns.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

[end section id="20112"]

